  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN151.1-kilavi">talaimaka<supplied>ṉ</supplied> piriviṉkaṇ vēṟupaṭṭa talaimakaḷ collitu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">What SHE said who had undergone changes during the separation from HIM.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="AN151.1">
              <l>tan<supplied>na</supplied>yan tuṟaivōrk kāṅkit tāyatayak</l>
              <l>kiṉṉamar kēḷiṉarō ṭēmuṟa keḻīi</l>
              <l>nakuta lāṟṟār <supplied>nal</supplied>kūrn tōreṉa</l>
              <l>mikuporu ṇiṉaiyu neñcamō ṭaruḷpiṟi</l>
              <l>tāpamaṉ vāḻi tōḻi kālviri</l>
              <l>puṟuvaḷi yeṟitoṟuṅ kalaṅkip poṟivarik</l>
              <l>kalaimāṉ ṟalaiyiṉ mutaṉmutaṟ kavarak</l>
              <l>kōṭalaṅ kavaṭṭa kuṟuṅkā luḻuñciṟ</l>
              <l>ṟāṟuciṉai viḷainta neṟṟa māṭumaka</l>
              <l>ḷarikōṟ paṟaiyi ṉaiyeṉa volikkum</l>
              <l>patukkait tāya cetukkai <supplied>nīḻal</supplied></l>
              <l>kaḷḷi muḷḷaraip poruntic cellunark</l>
              <l>kuṟuvatu kūṟuñ ciṟucen nāviṉ</l>
              <l>maṇipeyart taṉṉa teṇkuraṟ</l>
              <l>kaṇivāyp palliya kāṭiṟan tōrē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
                <l>Because of this pervasive perplexion there of him who keeps loving them, (1)</l>
                <l>saying “those who are poor cannot smile, (3)</l>
                <l>united to have pleasure with [their] kin whose beauty is pleasing!”, (2)</l>
                <l>he becomes someone whose consideration is different, oh friend,</l>
                <l>along with his heart that much thinks of wealth, as time goes by, (4f.)</l>
                <l>– he who has gone to traverse the wilderness of geckos with the mouths of astrologers, (15)</l>
                <l>with clear voices, as if bells were rung, (14)</l>
                <l>with little red tongues that talk of what will befall (13)</l>
                <l>those who go [there], staying on the thorny trunks of the spurges (12)</l>
                <l>in the blunted shade spread by the stone heaps, (11)</l>
                <l>where, wonderfully like the drums of the dancing girls with sticks that probe [them],</l>
                <l>the ripe seed pods sound on the bunchy branches (9f.)</l>
                <l>of the short-trunked Sirissa with pretty forked branches bending (8)</l>
                <l>s, stirred up whenever the moving wind beats [against them],</l>
                <l>the stag of the spotted deer with [its] head catches at root after root. (6f.)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>
